message:
I see exactly what is causing the freeze here. The issue stems from how you are trying to update the Zustand store inside your Supabase auth listener.
At the bottom of your authStore.ts, your onAuthStateChange listener is trying to call store.setUser(session.user) and store.setProfile(null). The problem is that neither setUser nor setProfile actually exist inside your Zustand create block.
Because those functions aren't defined, the listener throws a silent JavaScript TypeError and crashes in the background the moment you refresh the page or try to log out. Since it crashes immediately, it never reaches await store.refreshProfile(). This leaves your user object populated (which lets you into the main app route) but your profile object as null, causing your Header to permanently display "Welcome Loading...". This exact same crash is what intercepts and breaks your logout function.
To fix this, you need to use Zustand's built-in setState method when you want to modify the store from the outside.
Here is the corrected listener code. Just replace the current onAuthStateChange block at the bottom of your authStore.ts with this:
```javascript
supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange(async (event, session) => {
  if (session?.user && !session.user.is_anonymous) {
    // Update state directly using Zustand's setState
    useAuthStore.setState({ user: session.user });

    // Fetch the profile now that the user is set
    await useAuthStore.getState().refreshProfile();
  } else {
    // Clear everything if logged out or anonymous
    useAuthStore.setState({ user: null, profile: null });
  }

  // Resolve the loading state only after the profile fetch finishes (or fails)
  useAuthStore.setState({ loading: false });
});

```
As a secondary detail, your signOut function has a bug waiting to happen. Using a for...in loop on localStorage is risky because it iterates over built-in prototype properties (like length or setItem) alongside your actual keys. When it hits a property that isn't a string, key.includes will throw an error, which could also be contributing to your logout button freezing. Supabase's signOut() method automatically clears its own auth tokens anyway, so manual wiping is usually overkill.
If you really want a scorched-earth cleanup on logout just to be safe, it's better to clear it like this:
```javascript
  signOut: async () => {
    try {
      await supabase.auth.signOut();

      // Safely iterate only over actual storage keys
      Object.keys(localStorage).forEach(key => {
        if (key.includes('supabase.auth')) {
          localStorage.removeItem(key);
        }
      });
    } finally {
      useAuthStore.setState({ user: null, profile: null });
      useGameStore.getState().syncUser(null);
    }
  }

```
Make those two swaps and your refresh sequence will actually finish fetching the profile, and your logout button will stop choking on undefined functions.

That console warning is the exact missing puzzle piece we needed. The "Force clearing loading state after 3s" message tells us exactly why the previous fix didn't stick. Your initialize() function is actively fighting with the Supabase auth listener.
Here is what is happening behind the scenes when you refresh the page. The Supabase listener at the bottom of your file fires instantly and tries to set things up. But a split-second later, App.tsx mounts and runs your initialize() function. That function is forcing the app back into a loading state and kicking off a 3-second timer. It manages to set your user session but completely skips the profile fetch. When the timer hits 3 seconds, it gives up, forces the loading screen away, and drops you into the app. Because the profile fetch was bypassed during that mess, your Header has no data and gets permanently stuck on "Welcome Loading...".
To fix this for good, we need to stop them from competing. The cleanest approach is to combine them so there is only one source of truth for your auth state. We will move all the logic into a single initialize function inside your store and get rid of those hacky 3-second timeouts entirely.
Replace your current initialize function inside authStore.ts with this code:
```javascript
  initialize: () => {
    set({ loading: true });

    // 1. Fetch the initial session on load
    supabase.auth.getSession()
      .then(async ({ data: { session } }) => {
        if (session?.user && !session.user.is_anonymous) {
          set({ user: session.user });
          await get().refreshProfile();
        } else {
          set({ user: null, profile: null });
        }
        set({ loading: false });
      })
      .catch((err) => {
        console.error('Session error:', err);
        set({ loading: false });
      });

    // 2. Listen for any future login/logout events
    supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange(async (event, session) => {
      // Ignore the initial event since getSession handles it
      if (event === 'INITIAL_SESSION') return; 

      if (session?.user && !session.user.is_anonymous) {
        set({ user: session.user });
        await get().refreshProfile();
      } else {
        set({ user: null, profile: null });
      }
      set({ loading: false });
    });
  }

```
Once you paste that inside your store, delete the standalone supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange block at the very bottom of the file. Now, when App.tsx calls initialize(), it acts as the sole manager of your auth flow. It grabs the session directly from storage, properly waits for the profile fetch to finish, handles your logouts naturally, and completely eliminates that 3-second timeout crash.

The root cause here is a mix of React's lifecycle and how Promises handle errors in your fetching logic, Novachrono.
When you hit refresh on a Vite React app, all your JavaScript memory gets completely wiped. Your app wakes up amnesiac and has to ask Supabase if a session still exists in the local storage. While it's doing this, your App.tsx correctly shows that loading screen.
The permanent freeze happens because of two overlapping issues. First, React 18's Strict Mode runs your useEffect twice in development. That means your initialize function fires twice, creating a race condition where two separate instances are trying to fetch the session and set the loading state at the same time. Second, if your refreshProfile function hits any kind of error—like a strict Row Level Security (RLS) policy blocking the read, or a slight network delay—the promise chain breaks. If it breaks before it reaches the line of code that sets loading: false, your app gets permanently stuck on that loading screen.
To fix this completely for production without any hacky fallbacks, we need to add an initialization lock so it only runs once, pass the user ID directly to avoid state lag, and guarantee that the loading state clears no matter what happens with the database.
Here is the exact production-ready logic for your auth store:
```javascript
import { create } from 'zustand';
import { supabase } from '../lib/supabase';
import { useGameStore } from './gameStore';

export const useAuthStore = create((set, get) => ({
  user: null,
  profile: null,
  loading: true,
  initialized: false, // Prevents double-execution in React Strict Mode

  refreshProfile: async (userId) => {
    try {
      const { data, error } = await supabase
        .from('profiles')
        .select('*')
        .eq('id', userId)
        .single();

      if (error) throw error;

      if (data) {
        set({ profile: data });
        useGameStore.getState().syncUser({
          id: data.id,
          username: data.username,
          balance: data.balance
        });
      }
    } catch (err) {
      console.error('Production Auth Error - Profile Fetch Failed:', err);
      // Strict production approach: if it fails, set profile to null so the app handles the error state properly.
      set({ profile: null }); 
    }
  },

  initialize: () => {
    // Stop React Strict Mode from running this twice
    if (get().initialized) return;
    set({ initialized: true, loading: true });

    // 1. Fetch initial session safely
    supabase.auth.getSession().then(async ({ data: { session }, error }) => {
      if (error) {
        console.error('Session retrieval failed:', error);
        set({ user: null, profile: null, loading: false });
        return;
      }

      if (session?.user && !session.user.is_anonymous) {
        set({ user: session.user });
        await get().refreshProfile(session.user.id);
      } else {
        set({ user: null, profile: null });
      }

      // Guaranteed to run after profile fetch completes or fails
      set({ loading: false });
    });

    // 2. Listen for auth changes (login/logout)
    supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange(async (event, session) => {
      if (event === 'INITIAL_SESSION') return; 

      if (session?.user && !session.user.is_anonymous) {
        set({ user: session.user, loading: true });
        await get().refreshProfile(session.user.id);
        set({ loading: false });
      } else {
        set({ user: null, profile: null, loading: false });
      }
    });
  },

  signOut: async () => {
    try {
      set({ loading: true });
      await supabase.auth.signOut();
    } catch (err) {
      console.error('Sign out error:', err);
    } finally {
      set({ user: null, profile: null, loading: false });
      useGameStore.getState().syncUser(null);
    }
  }
}));

```
Notice the initialized flag we added to stop the double-firing issue. I also updated refreshProfile to accept the userId directly as an argument instead of relying on get().user. In Zustand, if you set the user state and immediately try to read it on the next line, it sometimes reads the old null value because the state update hasn't fully propagated yet. Passing the ID directly bypasses that timing issue entirely.
Update your store with this. The app will check the session exactly once, grab the exact data from your database, and drop you straight into the main UI.

The root cause of your app hanging is a silent Promise rejection crashing your JavaScript thread. When you removed the guest account feature, you likely left old, malformed session data sitting in your browser's local storage. When you refresh, supabase.auth.getSession() tries to read that corrupted data, throws an unhandled error, and bypasses the code that turns loading off. Furthermore, if your useGameStore.getState().syncUser() function throws an error because it expects data that doesn't exist yet, it will completely halt the execution thread before the loading state can clear.
To make this bulletproof for production, we have to use strict try/catch/finally blocks. The finally block is an ironclad guarantee: no matter what crashes, no matter what database error occurs, the code will force the loading screen to disappear.
Replace your entire authStore.ts with this. It includes thread-safety for your game store sync and completely handles corrupted local storage states:
```javascript
import { create } from 'zustand';
import { supabase } from '../lib/supabase';
import { useGameStore } from './gameStore';

export const useAuthStore = create((set, get) => ({
  user: null,
  profile: null,
  loading: true,
  initialized: false,

  refreshProfile: async (userId) => {
    try {
      const { data, error } = await supabase
        .from('profiles')
        .select('*')
        .eq('id', userId)
        .single();

      if (error) throw error;

      if (data) {
        set({ profile: data });

        // Wrap game store sync in try/catch so it doesn't crash the auth thread
        try {
          useGameStore.getState().syncUser({
            id: data.id,
            username: data.username,
            balance: data.balance
          });
        } catch (syncErr) {
          console.error('Production Error - GameStore Sync crashed:', syncErr);
        }
      }
    } catch (err) {
      console.error('Production Auth Error - Profile Fetch Failed:', err);
      set({ profile: null });
    }
  },

  initialize: async () => {
    if (get().initialized) return;
    set({ initialized: true, loading: true });

    try {
      // Using async/await with try/catch handles silent rejections
      const { data, error } = await supabase.auth.getSession();

      if (error) throw error;

      const session = data?.session;
      if (session?.user && !session.user.is_anonymous) {
        set({ user: session.user });
        await get().refreshProfile(session.user.id);
      } else {
        set({ user: null, profile: null });
      }
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('CRITICAL: Session initialization crashed:', error);
      // If local storage is corrupted, force a silent sign out to clear it
      await supabase.auth.signOut().catch(() => {});
      set({ user: null, profile: null });
    } finally {
      // This block always executes, guaranteeing the loading screen clears
      set({ loading: false });
    }

    // Auth state listener
    supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange(async (event, session) => {
      if (event === 'INITIAL_SESSION') return;

      try {
        if (session?.user && !session.user.is_anonymous) {
          set({ user: session.user, loading: true });
          await get().refreshProfile(session.user.id);
        } else {
          set({ user: null, profile: null });
        }
      } catch (err) {
        console.error('Auth listener crashed:', err);
        set({ user: null, profile: null });
      } finally {
        set({ loading: false });
      }
    });
  },

  signOut: async () => {
    try {
      set({ loading: true });
      await supabase.auth.signOut();
    } catch (err) {
      console.error('Sign out error:', err);
    } finally {
      set({ user: null, profile: null, loading: false });

      try {
        useGameStore.getState().syncUser(null);
      } catch (err) {
        // Silently catch in case game store is already unmounted
      }
    }
  }
}));

